Kincade Henry is a rising star in rodeo, making a name for himself as a talented tie-down roper. Born and raised in Mount Pleasant, Texas, Kincade has been involved in rodeo from a young age, following in the footsteps of his parents and siblings.

With a strong work ethic, dedication to his craft, and a passion for the sport, Kincade has already achieved significant success in his career, including multiple national championships.

In this article, we will explore Kincade’s life, career, and accomplishments, providing an in-depth look at this talented young rodeo athlete.

About Kincade Henry

Kincade Henry was born on March 13, 2002, in Mount Pleasant, Texas, to parents Chad and Melody Henry.

He has an older brother, Jace, who works as an engineer at an LNG plant in Cameron, Louisiana, and an older sister, Keely, who is also involved in rodeo and competed in college rodeo at A&M Commerce.

Kincade’s parents both qualified for the College National Finals Rodeo, and the family has a strong history in the sport.

Early Life

Kincade was introduced to rodeo at a young age, with his parents and siblings all competing in the sport. The family would often spend weekends traveling to rodeos and playdays, with Kincade learning to rope from his father, who was taught by the late R.E. Josey.

When Kincade’s sister Keely was forced to stop competing due to a heart condition, Kincade and his brother Jace also took a break from rodeo, with Kincade focusing on baseball for a time.

However, when Keely was cleared to compete again, the family returned to rodeo, reigniting Kincade’s passion for the sport.

Early Career

Kincade began competing in PRCA rodeo at the age of 18, but his rookie season was cut short due to the COVID-19 pandemic.

Despite this setback, Kincade continued to hone his skills and compete in college rodeo for Panola College in Carthage, Texas. In June 2023, Kincade won his second National Intercollegiate Rodeo Association championship in tie-down roping.

Professional Career

Impressive achievements and rapid growth have marked Kincade’s professional career. In 2021, he narrowly missed qualifying for the Wrangler National Finals Rodeo, finishing 18th in the standings.

However, this near-miss only fueled Kincade’s determination, and he has since made significant strides in his career.

In 2023, Kincade won the Home Of Champions Rodeo in Red Lodge, Montana, and was co-champion at the Rooftop Rodeo in Estes Park, Colorado. He also qualified for the Reno Rodeo finals in Nevada.

Kincade Henry’s Net Worth in 2023

Kincade Henry’s net worth in 2023 is estimated at around $500,000.

This figure is based on his career earnings as a tie-down roper, as well as any potential endorsement deals or other sources of income.

Career Earnings

Henry is a rising star in the rodeo world, and he has earned over $300,000 in his career so far. He qualified for the National Finals Rodeo (NFR) for the first time in 2022, and he finished the year ranked ninth in the world standings.

Endorsements

Kincade Henry has been associated with several rodeo events, but these are not endorsements. He was a co-champion at the Rooftop Rodeo in Estes Park, Colorado, and he was a first-time qualifier for the 2022 National Finals Rodeo.

Personal Details

Relationship

Kincade Henry is not married as of October 24, 2023. He is currently focused on his rodeo career, and he has not publicly announced any plans to get married in the near future.

Age

Kincade Henry was born on March 13, 2002, and is 21 years old as of October 24, 2023.

Height and Weight

According to the PRCA website, he is 6 feet 2 inches tall and weighs 185 pounds.

FAQs About Kincade Henry

What is Kincade Henry’s main rodeo event?

Kincade Henry primarily competes in tie-down roping.

Where is Kincade Henry from?

Kincade Henry is from Mount Pleasant, Texas.

Did Kincade Henry compete in college rodeo?

Yes, Kincade Henry competed in college rodeo for Panola College in Carthage, Texas, and won two consecutive National Intercollegiate Rodeo Association championships in tie-down roping.

Has Kincade Henry qualified for the Wrangler National Finals Rodeo?

Kincade narrowly missed qualifying for the Wrangler National Finals Rodeo in 2021, finishing 18th in the standings.

Who taught Kincade Henry to rope?

Kincade Henry learned to rope from his father, Chad Henry, who the late R.E. Josey taught.

Conclusion

Kincade Henry is a talented and dedicated rodeo athlete with a bright future ahead of him. With a strong foundation in the sport, a passion for competition, and a growing list of accomplishments, Kincade is well on his way to becoming a household name in rodeo. As he continues to compete and achieve success, there is no doubt that Kincade Henry will leave a lasting impact on the sport he loves.
